aws on his academic expertise and years of active participation within the Wikipedia community to take readers inside the site, illuminating how it functions and deconstructing its distinctive organization. Against a backdrop of misconceptions about its governance, authenticity, and accessibility, Jemielniak delivers the first ethnography of Wikipedia, revealing that it is not entirely at the mercy of the public: instead, it balances open access and power with a unique bureaucracy that takes a page from traditional organizational forms. Along the way, Jemielniak incorporates fascinating cases that highlight the tug of war among the participants as they forge ahead in this pioneering environment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aElectronic encyclopediasxSocial aspects. 0aOrganizational sociology. 4aInternet tribes. 4aWikipedia hierarchy. 4aWikipedia. 4aahierarchical organization. 4aforking. 4aonline communities. 4aopen collaboration. 4atrust online. 4avirtual bureaucracy. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Organizational Behavior.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804791205zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804791205423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804791205.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles